{{short description|concept of the underworld in ancient Mesopotamian culture}}
{{redirect|Kur|other uses|Kur (disambiguation)}}
[[File:Dumuzi aux enfers.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Ancient Sumerian [[cylinder seal]] impression showing the god [[Dumuzid]] being tortured in the underworld by ''[[gallu|galla]]'' demons]]

The '''ancient Mesopotamian underworld''', most often known in [[Sumerian language|Sumerian]] as '''Kur''', '''Irkalla''', '''Kukku''', '''Arali''', or '''Kigal''' and in [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]] as '''Erṣetu''', although it had many names in both languages, was a dark, dreary cavern located deep below the ground,{{sfn|Choksi|2014}}{{sfn|Barret|2007|pages=7–65}} where inhabitants were believed to continue "a shadowy version of life on earth".{{sfn|Choksi|2014}} The only food or drink was dry dust, but family members of the deceased would pour [[libations]] for them to drink. Unlike many other [[afterlife|afterlives]] of the ancient world, in the Sumerian [[underworld]], there was no final judgement of the deceased and the dead were neither punished nor rewarded for their deeds in life. A person's quality of existence in the underworld was determined by his or her conditions of burial.

The ruler of the underworld was the goddess [[Ereshkigal]], who lived in the palace '''Ganzir''', sometimes used as a name for the underworld itself. Her husband was either [[Gugalanna]], the "canal-inspector of Anu", or, especially in later stories, [[Nergal]], the god of death. After the [[Akkadian Empire|Akkadian Period]] ({{circa}} 2334 – 2154 BC), Nergal sometimes took over the role as ruler of the underworld. The seven gates of the underworld are guarded by a gatekeeper, who is named [[Neti (deity)|Neti]] in Sumerian. The god [[Namtar]] acts as Ereshkigal's ''sukkal'', or divine attendant. The dying god [[Dumuzid]] spends half the year in the underworld, while, during the other half, his place is taken by his sister, the scribal goddess [[Geshtinanna]], who records the names of the deceased. The underworld was also the abode of various demons, including the hideous child-devourer [[Lamashtu]], the fearsome wind demon and protector god [[Pazuzu]], and ''[[gallu|galla]]'', who dragged mortals to the underworld.

==Names==
The [[Sumer]]ians had a large number of different names which they applied to the underworld, including ''Arali'', ''Irkalla'', ''Kukku'', ''Ekur'', ''Kigal'', and ''Ganzir''.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=180}} All of these terms were later borrowed into Akkadian.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=180}} The rest of the time, the underworld was simply known by words meaning "earth" or "ground", including the terms ''Kur'' and ''Ki'' in Sumerian and the word ''erṣetu'' in Akkadian.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=180}} When used in reference to the underworld, the word ''Kur'' usually means "ground",{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=180}}{{sfn|Kramer|1961|page=76}}{{efn|In his book ''Sumerian Mythology'', first published in 1944 and revised in 1961, the scholar [[Samuel Noah Kramer]] argued that ''Kur'' could also refer to a personal entity, a monstrous dragon-like creature analogous to the Babylonian [[Tiamat]],{{sfn|Kramer|1961|pages=76–83}} but this interpretation was refuted as unsubstantiated by [[Thorkild Jacobsen]] in his essay "Sumerian Mythology: A Review Article"{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008a|pages=121–126}} and is not mentioned in more recent sources.}} but sometimes this meaning is conflated with another possible meaning of the word ''Kur'' as "mountain".{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=180}} The cuneiform sign for ''Kur'' was written ideographically with the cuneiform sign 𒆳, a pictograph of a mountain.{{sfn|Kramer|1961|page=110}} Sometimes the underworld is called the "land of no return", the "desert", or the "lower world".{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=180}} The most common name for the earth and the underworld in [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]] is ''erṣetu'',{{sfn|Horowitz|1998|pages=268–269}} but other names for the underworld include: ''ammatu'', ''arali'' / ''arallû'', ''bīt <sup>d</sup>dumuzi'' ("House of [[Dumuzi]]"), ''danninu'', ''erṣetu la târi'' ("Earth of No Return"), ''ganzer'' / ''kanisurra'', ''ḫaštu'', ''irkalla'', ''kiūru'', ''kukkû'' ("Darkness"), ''kurnugû'' ("Earth of No Return"), ''lammu'', ''mātu šaplītu'', and ''qaqqaru''.{{sfn|Horowitz|1998|pages=268–269}}

==Conditions==
[[File:Ur lyre.jpg|right|thumb|Detail of the "Peace" panel of the [[Standard of Ur]] from the [[Royal Cemetery at Ur]], showing a man playing a lyre. The Sumerians believed that, for the highly privileged, music could alleviate the bleak conditions of the underworld.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=25}}]] 

All souls went to the same afterlife,{{sfn|Choksi|2014}}{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=180}} and a person's actions during life had no effect on how the person would be treated in the world to come.{{sfn|Choksi|2014}} Unlike in the [[Ancient Egyptian afterlife beliefs|ancient Egyptian afterlife]], there was no process of judgement or evaluation for the deceased;{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=180}} they merely appeared before Ereshkigal, who would pronounce them dead,{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=180}} and their names would be recorded by the scribal goddess [[Geshtinanna]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=180}} The souls in Kur were believed to eat nothing but dry [[dust]]{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|pages=58, 180}} and family members of the deceased would ritually pour [[libation]]s into the dead person's grave through a clay pipe, thereby allowing the dead to drink.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=58}} For this reason, it was considered essential to have as many offspring as possible so that one's descendants could continue to provide libations for the dead person to drink for many years.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|pages=180–181}} Those who had died without descendants would suffer the most in the underworld, because they would have nothing to drink at all.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=181}} Sometimes the dead are described as naked or clothed in feathers like birds.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=180}}

Nonetheless, funerary evidence indicates that some people believed that the goddess [[Inanna]], Ereshkigal's younger sister, had the power to award her devotees with special favors in the afterlife.{{sfn|Choksi|2014}} During the [[Third Dynasty of Ur]] ({{circa}} 2112 – {{circa}} 2004 BC), it was believed that a person's treatment in the afterlife depended on how he or she was buried;{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=58}} those that had been given sumptuous burials would be treated well,{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=58}} but those who had been given poor burials would fare poorly.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=58}} Those who did not receive a proper burial, such as those who had died in fires and whose bodies had been burned or those who died alone in the desert, would have no existence in the underworld at all, but would simply cease to exist.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=181}} The Sumerians believed that, for the highly privileged, music could alleviate the bleak conditions of the underworld.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=25}}

==Geography==
The entrance to Kur was believed to be located in the [[Zagros mountains]] in the far east.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=114}} A staircase led down to the gates of the underworld.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=180}} The underworld itself is usually located even deeper below ground than the [[Abzu]], the body of freshwater which the ancient Mesopotamians believed lay deep beneath the earth.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=180}} In other, conflicting traditions, however, it seems to be located at a remote and inaccessible location on earth, possibly somewhere in the far west.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=180}} This alternate tradition is hinted at by the fact that the underworld is sometimes called "desert"{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=180}} and by the fact that actual rivers located far away from Sumer are sometimes referred to as the "river of the underworld".{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=180}} The underworld was believed to have seven gates, through which a soul needed to pass.{{sfn|Choksi|2014}} All seven gates were protected by [[dead bolt|bolt]]s.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=77}} The god [[Neti (deity)|Neti]] was the gatekeeper.{{sfn|Nemet-Nejat|1998|page=184}}{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=86}} Ereshkigal's ''sukkal'', or messenger, was the god [[Namtar]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=134}}{{sfn|Nemet-Nejat|1998|page=184}} The palace of Ereshkigal was known as Ganzir.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=77}}

At night, the sun-god [[Utu]] was believed to travel through the underworld as he journeyed to the east in preparation for the sunrise.{{sfn|Holland|2009|page=115}} One Sumerian literary work refers to Utu illuminating the underworld and dispensing judgement there{{sfn|Horowitz|1998|page=352}} and [[Shamash]] Hymn 31 (BWL 126) states that Utu serves as a judge of the dead in the underworld alongside the ''malku'', ''kusu'', and the [[Anunnaki]].{{sfn|Horowitz|1998|page=352}} On his way through the underworld, Utu was believed to pass through the garden of the sun-god,{{sfn|Holland|2009|page=115}} which contained trees that bore precious gems as fruit.{{sfn|Holland|2009|page=115}} The Sumerian hymn ''Inanna and Utu'' contains an [[Origin myth|etiological myth]] in which Utu's sister Inanna begs her brother Utu to take her to Kur,{{sfn|Leick|1998|page=91}} so that she may taste the fruit of a tree that grows there,{{sfn|Leick|1998|page=91}} which will reveal to her all the secrets of sex.{{sfn|Leick|1998|page=91}} Utu complies and, in Kur, Inanna tastes the fruit and becomes knowledgeable of sex.{{sfn|Leick|1998|page=91}} The hymn employs the same [[Motif (folkloristics)|motif]] found in the myth of ''Enki and Ninhursag'' and in the later Biblical story of [[Adam and Eve]].{{sfn|Leick|1998|page=91}}

==Inhabitants==
===Ereshkigal and family===
[[File:British Museum Queen of the Night.jpg|thumb|The "[[Burney Relief|Queen of Night Relief]]" ({{circa}} nineteenth or eighteenth century BC), which is believed to represent either Ereshkigal or her younger sister Inanna]]

A number of deities were believed by the ancient Mesopotamians to reside in the underworld.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=180}} The queen of the underworld was the goddess Ereshkigal.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=77}}{{sfn|Nemet-Nejat|1998|page=184}}{{sfn|Choksi|2014}} She was believed to live in palace known as Ganzir.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=77}} In earlier stories, her husband is [[Gugalanna]],{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=77}} but, in later myths, her husband is the god [[Nergal]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=77}}{{sfn|Nemet-Nejat|1998|page=184}} Her gatekeeper was the god Neti{{sfn|Nemet-Nejat|1998|page=184}} and her ''sukkal'' is the god [[Namtar]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=77}} In the poem ''Inanna's Descent into the Underworld'', Ereshkigal is described as Inanna's "older sister".{{sfn|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|page=55}}

Gugalanna is the first husband of Ereshkigal, the queen of the underworld.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=77}} His name probably originally meant "canal inspector of An"{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=77}} and he may be merely an alternative name for [[Ennugi]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=77}} The son of Ereshkigal and Gugalanna is [[Ninazu]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=77}} In ''Inanna's Descent into the Underworld'', Inanna tells the gatekeeper Neti that she is descending to the underworld to attend the funeral of "Gugalanna, the husband of my elder sister Ereshkigal".{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=77}}{{sfn|Kramer|1961|page=90}}{{sfn|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|page=55}} During the [[Akkadian Empire|Akkadian Period]] ({{circa}} 2334 – 2154 BC), Ereshkigal's role as the ruler of the underworld was assigned to Nergal, the god of death.{{sfn|Choksi|2014}}{{sfn|Nemet-Nejat|1998|page=184}} The Akkadians attempted to harmonize this dual rulership of the underworld by making Nergal Ereshkigal's husband.{{sfn|Choksi|2014}} Nergal is the deity most often identified as Ereshkigal's husband.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=136}} He was also associated with forest fires (and identified with the fire-god, [[Gibil]]{{sfn|Kasak|Veede|2001|page=28}}), fevers, plagues, and war.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=136}} In myths, he causes destruction and devastation.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=136}}

Ninazu is the son of Ereshkigal and the father of [[Ningishzida]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=137}} He is closely associated with the underworld.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=137}} He was mostly worshipped in [[Eshnunna]] during the third millennium BC, but he was later supplanted by the Hurrian storm god [[Tishpak]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=137}} A god named "Ninazu" was also worshipped at [[Enegi]] in southern Sumer,{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=137}} but this may be a different local god by the same name.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=137}} His divine beast was the ''[[mušḫuššu]]'', a kind of dragon, which was later given to Tishpak and then Marduk.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=137}}

[[Ningishzida]] is a god who normally lives in the underworld.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=138}} He is the son of Ninazu and his name may be etymologically derived from a phrase meaning "Lord of the Good Tree".{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=138}} In the Sumerian poem, ''The Death of Gilgamesh'', the hero [[Gilgamesh]] dies and meets Ningishzida, along with [[Dumuzid]], in the underworld.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=139}} [[Gudea]], the Sumerian king of the city-state of [[Lagash]], revered Ningishzida as his personal protector.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=139}} In the myth of [[Adapa]], Dumuzid and Ningishzida are described as guarding the gates of the highest Heaven.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|pages=139–140}} Ningishzida was associated with the constellation [[Hydra (constellation)|Hydra]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=140}}

===Other underworld deities===
[[File:Dieu mort.jpg|thumb|Terracotta plague dating to the [[Amorites|Amorite Period]] ({{circa}} 2000-1600 BC) showing a dead god (probably Dumuzid) resting in his coffin]]

Dumuzid, later known by the [[Language change|corrupted form]] Tammuz, is the ancient Mesopotamian god of shepherds{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=72}} and the primary consort of the goddess Inanna.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=72}} His sister is the goddess Geshtinanna.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=72}}{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=74–84}} In addition to being the god of shepherds, Dumuzid was also an agricultural deity associated with the growth of plants.{{sfn|Ackerman|2006|page=116}}{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008b|pages=87–88}} Ancient Near Eastern peoples associated Dumuzid with the springtime, when the land was fertile and abundant,{{sfn|Ackerman|2006|page=116}}{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008b|pages=83–84}} but, during the summer months, when the land was dry and barren, it was thought that Dumuzid had "died".{{sfn|Ackerman|2006|page=116}}{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008b|pages=83–87}} During the month of [[Tammuz (Babylonian calendar)|Dumuzid]], which fell in the middle of summer, people all across Sumer would mourn over his death.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=73}}{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008b|pages=74–84}} An enormous number of popular stories circulated throughout the Near East surrounding his death.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=73}}{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008b|pages=74–84}}

Geshtinanna is a rural agricultural goddess sometimes associated with [[dream interpretation]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=88}} She is the sister of Dumuzid, the god of shepherds.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=88}} In one story, she protects her brother when the ''[[gallu|galla]]'' demons come to drag him down to the underworld by hiding him in successively in four different places.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=88}} In another version of the story, she refuses to tell the ''galla'' where he is hiding, even after they torture her.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=88}} The ''galla'' eventually take Dumuzid away after he is betrayed by an unnamed "friend",{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=88}} but Inanna decrees that he and Geshtinanna will alternate places every six months, each spending half the year in the underworld while the other stays in Heaven.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=88}} While she is in the underworld, Geshtinanna serves as Ereshkigal's scribe.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=88}}

[[Lugal-irra and Meslamta-ea]] are a set of twin gods who were worshipped in the village of Kisiga, located in northern [[Babylonia]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=123}} They were regarded as guardians of doorways{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=124}} and they may have originally been envisioned as a set of twins guarding the gates of the underworld, who chopped the dead into pieces as they passed through the gates.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|pages=123–124}} During the [[Neo-Assyrian Empire|Neo-Assyrian Period]] (911 BC–609 BC), small depictions of them would be buried at entrances,{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=124}} with Lugal-irra always on the left and Meslamta-ea always on the right.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=124}} They are identical and are shown wearing horned caps and each holding an axe and a mace.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=124}} They are identified with the constellation [[Gemini (constellation)|Gemini]], which is named after them.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=124}}

Neti is the gatekeeper of the underworld.{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=87}} In the story of ''Inanna's Descent into the Underworld'', he leads Inanna through the seven gates of the underworld,{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=87}}{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=157–159}} removing one of her garments at each gate so that when she comes before Ereshkigal she is naked and symbolically powerless.{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=87}}{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=157–159}} [[Belet-Seri]] is a [[chthonic]] underworld goddess who was thought to record the names of the deceased as they entered the underworld.{{sfn|Jordan|2002|page=48}} [[Enmesarra]] is a minor deity of the underworld.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=76}} Seven or eight other minor deities were said to be his offspring.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=76}} His symbol was the ''suššuru'' (a kind of [[pigeon]]).{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=76}} In one incantation, Enmesarra and Ninmesharra, his female counterpart, are invoked as ancestors of [[Enki]] and as primeval deities.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=76}} Ennugi is "the canal inspector of the gods".{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=77}} He is the son of Enlil or Enmesarra{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=77}} and his wife is the goddess [[Nanibgal]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=77}} He is associated with the underworld{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=76}} and he may be Gugalanna, the first husband of Ereshkigal, under a different name.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=77}}

===Demons===
{{multiple image
